(* ======================================================
   Section G. Sanity checks.
   ====================================================== *)

(* G.1: Closure check. After integrating one full period T, verify
        ||X(T) - X(0)|| < integration tolerance. If not, T is wrong or
        IC has drift. *)

(* G.2: Self-consistency of sigma_3 on the 21 choreographies. This is a
        precondition: if sigma_3 isn't satisfied to high precision on the
        21 labeled choreographies, our integrator or ingestion is broken. *)

(* G.3: Cross-check on figure-eight (planar, equal-mass, well-known).
        Expected isotropy of figure-8:
           sigma_3  : YES (Z_3 choreography)
           alpha    : NO  (figure-8 is not a piano-trio; bodies trace a
                          single curve, not pairwise)
           beta     : YES (figure-8 has isoscele time-reversal symmetry --
                          this is the Chenciner-Montgomery Z_2 reflection
                          that makes the action minimum on D_3-fixed loops)
           gamma    : NO  (planar, z-reflection trivial)
           delta    : NO  (planar)
        Predicted descent under m_3 perturbation: 1 piano-trio family
        (from beta). This is a known reference point -- if our detector
        gets the figure-8 wrong, stop. *)

(* G.4: Conjugation closure. Verify that conjugating alpha by sigma_3
        gives an equivalent operator: sigma3 . alpha . sigma3^{-1}
        should equal ((23), 5T/6, +, I), which acts on a choreography
        the same way alpha does (since the choreography is itself
        sigma_3-invariant). If a choreography satisfies alpha but not
        the conjugate, there is an error in the detector or in the
        gauge fixing. *)


(* ======================================================
   Section H. Blowout hooks.
   ====================================================== *)

(* H.1: Replace the discrete classifier with a *continuous* "isotrophy
        score" vector  s(X) = (r_alpha, r_beta, r_gamma, r_delta).
        Cluster the 21 choreographies in s-space after removing the
        structural facetBeta direction. The sundog theorem predicts
        emergent residuals are either at numerical zero or O(1). If we
        see intermediate values, the theorem either needs a tolerance
        argument or has missed a residual generator. *)

(* H.2: Extend residualZ2candidates with composite operators of the form
        ((12), k*T/n, treverse?, zreflect?) for rational k/n. The current
        four are k/n in {0, 1/2}; if K_facet < K_emp, the missing daughters
        may live at other rational time shifts. (Beware of overcounting
        from conjugation by sigma_3 and from the template facet if so.) *)

(* H.3: Replace the 21-and-273 slice with the full 13315 stable planar
        catalog from Li-Li-Liao 2021. The same descent calculation,
        now S_3 -> Z_2 in the planar setting, predicts a similar
        ratio. Independent test. *)

(* H.4: Reverse direction -- predict choreographies from piano-trios.
        Given a piano-trio at m_3 ≠ 1, continue it to m_3 = 1 and
        check whether it converges to a Z_3 choreography or to a generic
        equal-mass orbit. The sundog theorem predicts: piano-trios with
        residual type alpha (or any of the four) ascend to choreographies;
        piano-trios that arose by other mechanisms (e.g., direct
        bifurcation from a Z_2-equilibrium) do not. *)

(* Facet correction for H.4: interpret "ascend" inside the Li-Liao ansatz
   facet. The post-grounding theorem predicts facet-visible piano-trios
   with emergent residual structure ascend to facet-visible choreographies;
   piano-trios produced by other mechanisms need not. *)


(* ======================================================
   End of workbench skeleton.
   ====================================================== *)
